    Platforms
    Minecart track
    Pressure plate Minecart track
    Spear trap
    All 3 wrenches + wire cutters
    999 wire
    Actuators
    Wood
    Picksaw
    Any type of block but lihzard brick works best.

  3. DicemanX Brain of Cthulhu

    Start a Conversation
    One thing to also consider in your farm: you can work on reducing gear requirements to virtually zero by adding 1 or more heart statues along the track you use for evasion. The statue(s) can sit on the wooden platforms just above the track, and each statue can have all 6 activation points connected to pressure plate tracks. This way you can generate 120 health per 10 seconds per statue.

    This isn't a suggested improvement since it does replace one set of resources (the gear) for a more scarce resource (heart statues), but it can carry more appeal if you can basically go in with a naked character and farm golems all day long . Still, your farm certainly works well as it is.

  6. Stahn Aileron Terrarian

    Start a Conversation
    So I'm guess the plate on the right are to activate the traps in sequence. Have you consider adding another track set under the main evasion track set as a Trap activation line the cart would run over just once?

    I'm just suggesting this so you can activate everything in one go vice having to activate the traps separately. The inner ramps force you to the top track, just like the original. The outer ramps let you bypass the bottom track by holding up as you ride up. (I wanted the outers to be inline with the main ramp, but the interconnection was futzy/inconsistent in behavior, so I just offset it to make it easier on myself.)

    On the flip side, now that I think about it, you can set it up so that holding up will let you travel to the top track, hit the pressure plates, then letting go of up will set you down onto the bottom track for normal operation. I realize my set up with the plates on the bottom isn't as hands-off/-free between Golem summons. As I have it now, you had to hold up for each session after the initial trap activations. Setting the bottom track as default operation and the upper as trap activation makes it operate more like your original design after the initial run. It also eliminates a set of intermediate ramps (you don't need the inner set anymore).

  14. Stahn Aileron Terrarian

    Start a Conversation
    MrTheEpicNinja said: ↑
    The problem i had with this is when you go back and forth it wouldnt have time to reset the trap closest to the end when i bounce back. I tried teleporters but it didnt work
    Click to expand...
    In what way? I didn't seem to have any problems when I was testing it out as I have it pictured above. I could easily turn on or off the traps simply by holding the UP (W) key. Letting go would automatically bounce me to the bottom, no-plate track. Holding DOWN (S) would get me back to the bottom point, just like in your video.

    OH! Now I get what you mean! No, no, no. ^_^ If you look closely, the switches are tied to TIMERS as well (upper right), right by the Traps in my image. I forgot to place lighting there. You don't repeatedly activate the track plates to trigger the traps. The way I have the tracks set up, you only go onto the plate tracks if you hold the W key. Once you're on the top tracks, letting go of W will bounce you back down to the bottom track, which has nothing on it. This is the "steady" or default state.

    So, for the first Golem, up hold W as you go up the ramp. When you're on the top tracks, you let go of W, trigger the timers, then bounce down to the bottom tracks. When the Golem dies, you hold S to ride back down, collecting the drop and summon another Golem.

    Look closely at how I have the tracks set up. You'll see what I mean. (It's clearest on the left side; less wire cluttering the area.)

    Congrats on MKII; it's getting progressively slicker.

    In the video you say that a square room is a lot better for this. Am I'm missing something, I don't see how that would be an issue in this setup, provided you have space for the track...?
    MrTheEpicNinja said: ↑
    I think that the box should be 13 blocks instead of 14 to completely trap in the golem. Therefore allowing no movemet whatsoever.
    Click to expand...
    Try interior space dimensions of 9x9 tiles. That's what I used in my "Super Golem!" video. Height above altar surface was particular too. And that one up-sloped block was needed to stop him jumping down through the floor.


    Stahn Aileron said: ↑
    They don't do anything if an entity is moving upward through them
    Click to expand...
    Correct, unless they are also moving sideways onto a new plate (whilst going up).

    Regarding @Stahn Aileron 's direct minecart trap activation idea. It's a good plan, but try to keep things simple. Try starting from the speed of the mine cart and figuring out the length of track you will need for staggering plate activations over the 2s length of the spear trap's cool-down.

    For example, minecarts top out at 48.8 tiles/s, so you'd need a length of track 98 tiles long. A bit unwieldy, so you cold instead try activating all the trap timers off a single booster. At 15 tiles/s the timer/trap activating trap length would need to be about 30 tiles long (2s x 15tiles/s). Which should fit in the current room easily. You should then start by dropping onto a single booster (like this) that runs you along the activation line once, before depositing you into the main loop, where you'll then stay.

    Alternatively, you could take out the timers altogether, by continuously running back and forth along the track with staggered pressure plates (connected directly to the traps, only). In this instance you'd want to make the length (i.e. width) of the track section a multiple of the minecart speed. So at full speed make it 49tiles long. Unfortunately this will activate all traps within 1s (e.g. the first run right to left) and then they'll all be on cooldown for the return trip of 1s. (As i think you were saying, @MrTheEpicNinja .) The Golem's body is fairly big though, so allows a bit of buffer time in the activation spacings. You could increase the trap firing staggering by starting in the middle of the plate track too, hitting the plates for traps connected to the left side of the track twice before hitting the ones on the right the first time, 1s later (for example).

    I've been working on tracktronic trap timing mechanism for a forthcoming video/guide, so I'll be able to show more ideas down the road a little.

    This is the reason I have 2 booster pair sets on the activation line while keeping the original 3x sets he has on the main ramp. I have the activation boosters set up to slow the cart down (3x (45bps) - 2x (30bps) = 15bps effective) to activate the traps with proper timing within reasonable space. (I followed nekojita's example at the end of his cart speed video.) Once the traps are activated, the second booster set ramps you back up to dodging speed before dumping you back on the main line track.

  18. Full Metal Kirby Official Terrarian

    Start a Conversation
    So, being inspired by the interest in golem murdering, I decided to try my hand at compressing the design.



    (8 spaces between each tooth, except the top one which there's only 4 spaces)

    'tis rather ugly since I wasn't sure my idea would work (and have yet to pretty it up), but as you can probably guess from the images, the golem is hoikable -- vertically at least, haven't tested horizontal.

    Slow movement on the tracks equates to very rarely being hit by lasers in phase 1 (out of range of the fists entirely), and still very rarely in phase 2. Heck, if you added teleporters to the ends rather than relying on bouncing, you'd probably never be hit by lasers in phase 1.

    The bird engine can of course be replaced by whatever activation means one sees fit for the timers.

    Feel free to use the design should it tickle your fancy.

    Yeah, there's definitely a handful of things that can still be improved on it to make it smaller. I just figured I'd post my early design to see what ideas it might spark.

    Edit: Speaking of compressing, here's what I've ended up with:

    (Footprint of 33w/44h)

    This setup should:
    A) Fit within most temples without requiring a Picksaw.
    B) Make it so the golem never hits you, ever.
    C) Requires no spikey ball traps.

    Of course, should one find the teleporting noise a bother, you can always remove them and block the golem fists using spikey ball traps instead. Should be more or less just as effective for not being hit, though you might have to move the golem farther away.

    Also, while the inward curves at the golems fist level might just look like an aesthetic, it plays the important role of insuring that its drops don't land on the hoiks on the sides.
